okens': None, 'reasoning_tokens': 228, 'rejected_prediction_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 267}, 'prompt_tokens_details': {'audio_tokens': None, 'cached_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 7184}}, 'model_provider': 'openai', 'model_name': 'qwen3.5-plus', 'system_fingerprint': None, 'id': 'chatcmpl-b1fb65c7-4701-9cb1-a231-7a4a9707abcd', 'finish_reason': 'tool_calls', 'logprobs': None}, name='researcher', id='lc_run--019c9dd5-b558-7c50-a9b4-2c0ba41ac7a0-0', tool_calls=[{'name': 'academic_search', 'args': {'__arg1': 'marine species named after magazine publisher museum founder'}, 'id': 'call_93121112dca64bf7aa30bfe3', 'type': 'tool_call'}], invalid_tool_calls=[], usage_metadata={'input_tokens': 7184, 'output_tokens': 267, 'total_tokens': 7451, 'input_token_details': {}, 'output_token_details': {'reasoning': 228}}), ToolMessage(content="Published: 2024-07-05\nTitle: Automating Venture Capital: Founder assessment using LLM-powered segmentation, feature engineering and automated labeling techniques\nAuthors: Ekin Ozince, Yiğit Ihlamur\nSummary: This study explores the application of large language models (LLMs) in venture capital (VC) decision-making, focusing on predicting startup success based on founder characteristics. We utilize LLM prompting techniques, like chain-of-thought, to generate features from limited data, then extract insights through statistics and machine learning. Our results reveal potential relationships between certain founder characteristics and success, as well as demonstrate the effectiveness of these characteristics in prediction. This framework for integrating ML techniques and LLMs has vast potential for improving startup success prediction, with important implications for VC firms seeking to optimize their investment strategies.\n\nPublished: 2022-04-08\nTitle: Design of an Optimal Testbed for Tracking of Tagged Marine Megafauna\nAuthors: Talmon Alexandri, Roee Diamant\nSummary: Underwater acoustic technologies are a key component for exploring the behavior of marine megafauna such as sea turtles, sharks, and seals. The animals are marked with acoustic devices (tags) that periodically emit signals encoding the device's ID along with sensor data such as depth, temperature, or the dominant acceleration axis - data that is collected by a network of deployed receivers. In this work, we aim to optimize the locations of receivers for best tracking of acoustically tagged marine megafauna. The outcomes of such tracking allows the evaluation of the animals' motion patterns, their hours of activity, and their social interactions. In particular, we focus on how to determine the receivers' deployment positions to maximize the coverage area in which the tagged animals can be tracked. For example, an overly-condensed deployment may not allow accurate tracking, whereas a sparse one, may lead to a small coverage area due to too few detections. We formalize the question of where to best deploy the receivers as a non-convex constraint optimization problem that takes into account the local environment and the specifications of the tags, and offer a sub-optimal, low-complexity solution that can be applied to large testbeds. Numerical investigation for three stimulated sea environments shows that our proposed method is able to increase the localization coverage area by 30%, and results from a test case experiment demonstrate similar performance in a real sea environment. We share the implementation of our work to help researchers set up their own acoustic observatory.\n\nPublished: 2004-10-06\nTitle: Disabled Access for Museum Websites\nAuthors: Jonathan P. Bowen\nSummary: Physical disabled access is something that most museums consider very seriously. Indeed, there are normally legal requirements to do so. However, online disabled access is still a relatively novel field. Most museums have not yet considered the issues in depth. The Human-Computer Interface for their websites is normally tested with major browsers, but not with specialist browsers or against the relevant accessibility and validation standards. We consider the current state of the art in this area and mention an accessibility survey of some museum websites.", name='academic_search', id='781d07f8-665b-492a-8b5a-b7a30f7518da', tool_call_id='call_93121112dca64bf7aa30bfe3'), AIMessage(content='', additional_kwargs={'refusal': None}, response_metadata={'token_usage': {'completion_tokens': 57, 'prompt_tokens': 7882, 'total_tokens': 7939, 'completion_tokens_details': {'accepted_prediction_tokens': None, 'audio_tokens': None, 'reasoning_tokens': 0, 'rejected_prediction_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 57}, 'prompt_tokens_details': {'audio_tokens': None, 'cached_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 7882}}, 'model_provider': 'openai', 'model_name': 'qwen3.5-plus', 'system_fingerprint': None, 'id': 'chatcmpl-39031cc1-2fb8-931b-bbcf-57d95834ed2d', 'finish_reason': 'tool_calls', 'logprobs': None}, name='researcher', id='lc_run--019c9dd5-cb27-7732-b87a-aa7186a795f5-0', tool_calls=[{'name': 'common_search', 'args': {'query': '"died January 8" 2021 2022 2023 "Frank" "Steve" magazine publisher'}, 'id': 'call_7e8270804f654b90be1780f5', 'type': 'tool_call'}], invalid_tool_calls=[], usage_metadata={'input_tokens': 7882, 'output_tokens': 57, 'total_tokens': 7939, 'input_token_details': {}, 'output_token_details': {'reasoning': 0}}), ToolMessage(content="SYSTEM ALERT: You have used the tool 'common_search' 3 times, which is the limit for a single tool. You MUST switch to a DIFFERENT search tool (e.g., use 'academic_search' or 'web_search' instead of 'common_search'). Using the same tool repeatedly is ineffective. TRY ANOTHER TOOL.", name='common_search', id='3f3f6412-f4ca-45be-afbf-06d2e3b5e294', tool_call_id='call_7e8270804f654b90be1780f5'), AIMessage(content='', additional_kwargs={'refusal': None}, response_metadata={'token_usage': {'completion_tokens': 43, 'prompt_tokens': 8021, 'total_tokens': 8064, 'completion_tokens_details': {'accepted_prediction_tokens': None, 'audio_tokens': None, 'reasoning_tokens': 0, 'rejected_prediction_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 43}, 'prompt_tokens_details': {'audio_tokens': None, 'cached_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 8021}}, 'model_provider': 'openai', 'model_name': 'qwen3.5-plus', 'system_fingerprint': None, 'id': 'chatcmpl-f8b2bc36-c648-9dd0-8c47-f409554b24b5', 'finish_reason': 'tool_calls', 'logprobs': None}, name='researcher', id='lc_run--019c9dd5-cf94-7520-beea-f41f72b032c5-0', tool_calls=[{'name': 'academic_search', 'args': {'__arg1': 'three marine species named in honor person died 2022'}, 'id': 'call_2d256c73326f45199bf3ad69', 'type': 'tool_call'}], invalid_tool_calls=[], usage_metadata={'input_tokens': 8021, 'output_tokens': 43, 'total_tokens': 8064, 'input_token_details': {}, 'output_token_details': {'reasoning': 0}}), ToolMessage(content='Published: 2022-06-15\nTitle: CMNEROne at SemEval-2022 Task 11: Code-Mixed Named Entity Recognition by leveraging multilingual data\nAuthors: Suman Dowlagar, Radhika Mamidi\nSummary: Identifying named entities is, in general, a practical and challenging task in the field of Natural Language Processing. Named Entity Recognition on the code-mixed text is further challenging due to the linguistic complexity resulting from the nature of the mixing. This paper addresses the submission of team CMNEROne to the SEMEVAL 2022 shared task 11 MultiCoNER. The Code-mixed NER task aimed to identify named entities on the code-mixed dataset. Our work consists of Named Entity Recognition (NER) on the code-mixed dataset by leveraging the multilingual data. We achieved a weighted average F1 score of 0.7044, i.e., 6% greater than the baseline.\n\nPublished: 2022-11-22\nTitle: CHC-COMP 2022: Competition Report\nAuthors: Emanuele De Angelis, Hari Govind V K\nSummary: CHC-COMP 2022 is the fifth edition of the competition of solvers for Constrained Horn Clauses. The competition was run in March 2022; the results were presented at the 9th Workshop on Horn Clauses for Verification and Synthesis held in Munich, Germany, on April 3, 2022. This edition featured six solvers, and eight tracks consisting of sets of linear and nonlinear clauses with constraints over linear integer arithmetic, linear real arithmetic, arrays, and algebraic data types. This report provides an overview of the organization behind the competition runs: it includes the technical details of the competition setup as well as presenting the results of the 2022 edition.\n\nPublished: 2022-06-08\nTitle: Motif Mining and Unsupervised Representation Learning for BirdCLEF 2022\nAuthors: Anthony Miyaguchi, Jiangyue Yu, Bryan Cheungvivatpant, Dakota Dudley, Aniketh Swain\nSummary: We build a classification model for the BirdCLEF 2022 challenge using unsupervised methods. We implement an unsupervised representation of the training dataset using a triplet loss on spectrogram representation of audio motifs. Our best model performs with a score of 0.48 on the public leaderboard.', name='academic_search', id='765bcb09-8f98-478a-959d-af740f5b473f', tool_call_id='call_2d256c73326f45199bf3ad69'), AIMessage(content='# Research Report: Identifying the Museum Founder\n\n## Problem Statement\n\nThe research task seeks to identify an individual with the following specific characteristics:\n- Founded a museum established between 1972 and 1975 (inclusive)\n- As of December 31, 2023, the museum is situated on the second floor of a building\n- The museum is located 24 to 25 miles (aerial distance) from a library that opened between 1992 and 1995 and is over 70,000 square feet\n- Was the editor and publisher of a magazine for over thirty years\n- Three marine species have been named in their honor\n- Had a parent with the first name Frank and a sibling with the first name Steve\n- Passed away on January 8 between 2021 and 2023 (inclusive) in a country different from their birthplace\n- Received an award in 2014 in recognition of their work\n\n## Research Findings\n\n### Search Strategy and Limitations\n\nMultiple search queries were executed using the available search tools (common_search and academic_search) to identify the individual matching these highly specific criteria. The searches focused on combinations of:\n- Death date (January 8, 2021-2023)\n- Museum founder status\n- Magazine publisher/editor role\n- Marine species named in honor\n- Family names (Frank as parent, Steve as sibling)\n\n### Key Search Results\n\n**Death Date Searches:**\nSearches for individuals who died on January 8 between 2021-2023 did not return specific matches that could be cross-referenced with the other criteria (museum founder, magazine publisher, marine species honors).\n\n**Marine Species Named After Individuals:**\nSome search results mentioned marine organisms named after various researchers and contributors, including:\n- Several species named after Dr. Otto Maas, Dr. Bernard John McAlice, and others\n- New seahorse species named after underwater photographers and divers (Helmut Debelius, Mike Severn)\n- However, none of these matched the complete profile of the individual in question\n\n**Museum and Magazine Publisher Connections:**\nSearches for museum founders who were also long-time magazine publishers did not yield specific matches with the death date and family name criteria.\n\n### Information Gaps\n\nThe following critical information could not be confirmed through the available searches:\n1. The specific name of the individual matching all criteria\n2. The name and location of the museum founded between 1972-1975\n3. The name of the magazine they edited/published for over 30 years\n4. The three specific marine species named in their honor\n5. Confirmation of parent named Frank and sibling named Steve\n6. The award received in 2014\n7. Birth and death countries to confirm they were different\n8. The library located 24-25 miles from the museum\n\n## Conclusion\n\nBased on the searches conducted, I was unable to definitively identify the individual matching all the specified criteria. The combination of highly specific details (exact death date of January 8, specific year ranges, family member names, number of marine species, and geographic constraints) suggests this is a very specific person, but the available search results did not contain sufficient information to make a positive identification.\n\nThe research was limited by:\n- Maximum search tool call limit (5 calls)\n- Search results that did not contain comprehensive biographical information linking all the criteria\n- Inability to access detailed obituary or biographical databases that might contain the family name information (Frank, Steve)\n\nTo complete this research successfully, additional search capabilities would be needed, particularly:\n- Access to comprehensive obituary databases\n- Marine species etymology databases\n- Museum founding records with founder biographical information\n- Magazine publisher historical records\n\n## References\n\n- [Biographical Etymology of Marine Organism Names](https://www.bemon.loven.gu.se/petymol.m.html)\n\n- [List of species named after the COVID-19 pandemic - Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_species_named_after_the_COVID-19_pandemic)\n\n- [2025 Annual Marine Photographer Competition Results](https://m.toutiao.com/a1850620858833992/)\n\n- [Five New Seahorse Species Discovered in Red Sea and Indonesian Waters](https://baijiahao.baidu.com/s?id=1826086105331525678)\n\n- [Automating Venture Capital: Founder assessment using LLM-powered segmentation](https://arxiv.org/abs/2407.04123)\n\n- [Design of an Optimal Testbed for Tracking of Tagged Marine Megafauna](https://arxiv.org/abs/2204.04086)', additional_kwargs={}, response_metadata={}, name='researcher', id='726999de-5098-4164-9b84-d09a22e0845e', tool_calls=[], invalid_tool_calls=[]), HumanMessage(content="# Research Topic\n\nResearch Plan to Identify the Individual\n\n# Completed Research Steps\n\n## Completed Step 1: Search for Individual Matching Death Date and Biographical Details\n\n<finding>\n# Research Report: Identifying the Museum Founder\n\n## Problem Statement\n\nThe research task seeks to identify an individual with the following specific characteristics:\n- Founded a museum established between 1972 and 1975 (inclusive)\n- As of December 31, 2023, the museum is situated on the second floor of a building\n- The museum is located 24 to 25 miles (aerial distance) from a library that opened between 1992 and 1995 and is over 70,000 square feet\n- Was the editor and publisher of a magazine for over thirty years\n- Three marine species have been named in their honor\n- Had a parent with the first name Frank and a sibling with the first name Steve\n- Passed away on January 8 between 2021 and 2023 (inclusive) in a country different from their birthplace\n- Received an award in 2014 in recognition of their work\n\n## Research Findings\n\n### Search Strategy and Limitations\n\nMultiple search queries were executed using the available search tools (common_search and academic_search) to identify the individual matching these highly specific criteria. The searches focused on combinations of:\n- Death date (January 8, 2021-2023)\n- Museum founder status\n- Magazine publisher/editor role\n- Marine species named in honor\n- Family names (Frank as parent, Steve as sibling)\n\n### Key Search Results\n\n**Death Date Searches:**\nSearches for individuals who died on January 8 between 2021-2023 did not return specific matches that could be cross-referenced with the other criteria (museum founder, magazine publisher, marine species honors).\n\n**Marine Species Named After Individuals:**\nSome search results mentioned marine organisms named after various researchers and contributors, including:\n- Several species named after Dr. Otto Maas, Dr. Bernard John McAlice, and others\n- New seahorse species named after underwater photographers and divers (Helmut Debelius, Mike Severn)\n- However, none of these matched the complete profile of the individual in question\n\n**Museum and Magazine Publisher Connections:**\nSearches for museum founders who were also long-time magazine publishers did not yield specific matches with the death date and family name criteria.\n\n### Information Gaps\n\nThe following critical information could not be confirmed through the available searches:\n1. The specific name of the individual matching all criteria\n2. The name and location of the museum founded between 1972-1975\n3. The name of the magazine they edited/published for over 30 years\n4. The three specific marine species named in their honor\n5. Confirmation of parent named Frank and sibling named Steve\n6. The award received in 2014\n7. Birth and death countries to confirm they were different\n8. The library located 24-25 miles from the museum\n\n## Conclusion\n\nBased on the searches conducted, I was unable to definitively identify the individual matching all the specified criteria. The combination of highly specific details (exact death date of January 8, specific year ranges, family member names, number of marine species, and geographic constraints) suggests this is a very specific person, but the available search results did not contain sufficient information to make a positive identification.\n\nThe research was limited by:\n- Maximum search tool call limit (5 calls)\n- Search results that did not contain comprehensive biographical information linking all the criteria\n- Inability to access detailed obituary or biographical databases that might contain the family name information (Frank, Steve)\n\nTo complete this research successfully, additional search capabilities would be needed, particularly:\n- Access to comprehensive obituary databases\n- Marine species etymology databases\n- Museum founding records with founder biographical information\n- Magazine publisher historical records\n\n## References\n\n- [Biographical Etymology of Marine Organism Names](https://www.bemon.loven.gu.se/petymol.m.html)\n\n- [List of species named after the COVID-19 pandemic - Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_species_named_after_the_COVID-19_pandemic)\n\n- [2025 Annual Marine Photographer Competition Results](https://m.toutiao.com/a1850620858833992/)\n\n- [Five New Seahorse Species Discovered in Red Sea and Indonesian Waters](https://baijiahao.baidu.com/s?id=1826086105331525678)\n\n- [Automating Venture Capital: Founder assessment using LLM-powered segmentation](https://arxiv.org/abs/2407.04123)\n\n- [Design of an Optimal Testbed for Tracking of Tagged Marine Megafauna](https://arxiv.org/abs/2204.04086)\n</finding>\n\n# Current Step\n\n## Title\n\nResearch Museum Founded 1972-1975 and Magazine Publisher Details\n\n## Description\n\nFind museums established between 1972-1975 that are located on the second floor of a building (as of 2023), and identify their founders who were also long-time magazine editors/publishers. Search for magazine publishers who worked for over 30 years and received awards in 2014.\n\n## Locale\n\nen-US\n\nIMPORTANT: Your response MUST be written entirely in the language specified in the 'Locale' section above (which is en-US). This applies to all sections of your response, including headers, content, and conclusions.\n\nIMPORTANT: Review the 'Completed Research Steps' above carefully. If the information required for the 'Current Step' has already been gathered in previous steps, DO NOT perform new searches. Instead, synthesize the existing information to answer the current step immediately. Only use tools if you are missing specific critical details.", additional_kwargs={}, response_metadata={}), HumanMessage(content='IMPORTANT: DO NOT include inline citations in the text. Instead, track all sources and include a References section at the end using link reference format. Include an empty line between each citation for better readability. Use this format for each reference:\n- [Source Title](URL)\n\n- [Another Source](URL)', additional_kwargs={}, response_metadata={}, name='system')]}
