eral \n\n*   [What links here](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special:WhatLinksHere/Deaths_in_January_2022 "List of all English Wikipedia pages containing links to this page [j]")\n*   [Related changes](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special:RecentChangesLinked/Deaths_in_January_2022 "Recent changes in pages linked from this page [k]")\n*   [Upload file](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:File_Upload_Wizard "Upload files [u]")\n*   [Permanent link](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Deaths_in_January_2022&oldid=1339882719 "Permanent link to this revision of this page")\n*   [Page information](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Deaths_in_January_2022&action=info "More information about this page")\n*   [Cite this page](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Special:CiteThisPage&page=Deaths_in_January_2022&id=1339882719&wpFormIdentifier=titleform "Information on how to cite this page")\n*   [Get shortened URL](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Special:UrlShortener&url=https%3A%2F%2Fen.wikipedia.org%2Fwiki%2FDeaths_in_January_2022)\n*   [Download QR code](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Special:QrCode&url=https%3A%2F%2Fen.wikipedia.org%2Fwiki%2FDeaths_in_January_2022)\n\n Print/export \n\n*   \n\n...(content truncated due to length)...', name='crawl_tool', id='7fefa265-4da0-4fea-8793-afcc60071a91', tool_call_id='call_0318d89053b043be8f4530b5'), AIMessage(content='', additional_kwargs={'refusal': None}, response_metadata={'token_usage': {'completion_tokens': 106, 'prompt_tokens': 19478, 'total_tokens': 19584, 'completion_tokens_details': {'accepted_prediction_tokens': None, 'audio_tokens': None, 'reasoning_tokens': 56, 'rejected_prediction_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 106}, 'prompt_tokens_details': {'audio_tokens': None, 'cached_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 19478}}, 'model_provider': 'openai', 'model_name': 'qwen3.5-plus', 'system_fingerprint': None, 'id': 'chatcmpl-67fa6313-3ace-9ea6-8d17-f0532eda08d8', 'finish_reason': 'tool_calls', 'logprobs': None}, name='researcher', id='lc_run--019c9dd7-8313-76b1-86a4-e82811729811-0', tool_calls=[{'name': 'common_search', 'args': {'query': '"January 8, 2022" death "magazine" "museum" founder publisher'}, 'id': 'call_e89495cb26324837b2906dea', 'type': 'tool_call'}], invalid_tool_calls=[], usage_metadata={'input_tokens': 19478, 'output_tokens': 106, 'total_tokens': 19584, 'input_token_details': {}, 'output_token_details': {'reasoning': 56}}), ToolMessage(content="SYSTEM ALERT: You have used the tool 'common_search' 3 times, which is the limit for a single tool. You MUST switch to a DIFFERENT search tool (e.g., use 'academic_search' or 'web_search' instead of 'common_search'). Using the same tool repeatedly is ineffective. TRY ANOTHER TOOL.", name='common_search', id='fd0e91a9-4c48-4b35-8187-c0cd81fd0cfa', tool_call_id='call_e89495cb26324837b2906dea'), AIMessage(content='', additional_kwargs={'refusal': None}, response_metadata={'token_usage': {'completion_tokens': 218, 'prompt_tokens': 19609, 'total_tokens': 19827, 'completion_tokens_details': {'accepted_prediction_tokens': None, 'audio_tokens': None, 'reasoning_tokens': 173, 'rejected_prediction_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 218}, 'prompt_tokens_details': {'audio_tokens': None, 'cached_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 19609}}, 'model_provider': 'openai', 'model_name': 'qwen3.5-plus', 'system_fingerprint': None, 'id': 'chatcmpl-2034f77e-4c82-9f8a-9717-ace602e2b867', 'finish_reason': 'tool_calls', 'logprobs': None}, name='researcher', id='lc_run--019c9dd7-8d5f-7a81-8990-79a4ec774cf9-0', tool_calls=[{'name': 'academic_search', 'args': {'__arg1': 'species named after "Frank" "Steve" magazine publisher malacology'}, 'id': 'call_5cc9773fe8fd43beaad4fe32', 'type': 'tool_call'}], invalid_tool_calls=[], usage_metadata={'input_tokens': 19609, 'output_tokens': 218, 'total_tokens': 19827, 'input_token_details': {}, 'output_token_details': {'reasoning': 173}}), ToolMessage(content='Published: 2014-01-03\nTitle: An Affine Invariant Linear Convergence Analysis for Frank-Wolfe Algorithms\nAuthors: Simon Lacoste-Julien, Martin Jaggi\nSummary: We study the linear convergence of variants of the Frank-Wolfe algorithms for some classes of strongly convex problems, using only affine-invariant quantities. As in Guelat & Marcotte (1986), we show the linear convergence of the standard Frank-Wolfe algorithm when the solution is in the interior of the domain, but with affine invariant constants. We also show the linear convergence of the away-steps variant of the Frank-Wolfe algorithm, but with constants which only depend on the geometry of the domain, and not any property of the location of the optimal solution. Running these algorithms does not require knowing any problem specific parameters.\n\nPublished: 2010-07-29\nTitle: Identifying the Rooted Species Tree from the Distribution of Unrooted Gene Trees under the Coalescent\nAuthors: Elizabeth S. Allman, James H. Degnan, John A. Rhodes\nSummary: Gene trees are evolutionary trees representing the ancestry of genes sampled from multiple populations. Species trees represent populations of individuals -- each with many genes -- splitting into new populations or species. The coalescent process, which models ancestry of gene copies within populations, is often used to model the probability distribution of gene trees given a fixed species tree. This multispecies coalescent model provides a framework for phylogeneticists to infer species trees from gene trees using maximum likelihood or Bayesian approaches. Because the coalescent models a branching process over time, all trees are typically assumed to be rooted in this setting. Often, however, gene trees inferred by traditional phylogenetic methods are unrooted.\n  We investigate probabilities of unrooted gene trees under the multispecies coalescent model. We show that when there are 4 species with one gene sampled per species, the distribution of unrooted gene tree topologies identifies the unrooted species tree topology and some, but not all, information in the species tree edges (branch lengths). The location of the root on the species tree is not identifiable in this situation. However, for 5 or more species with one gene sampled per species, we show that the distribution of unrooted gene tree topologies identifies the rooted species tree topology and all its internal branch lengths. The length of any pendent branch leading to a leaf of the species tree is also identifiable for any species from which more than one gene is sampled.\n\nPublished: 2005-11-21\nTitle: The Availability and Persistence of Web References in D-Lib Magazine\nAuthors: Frank McCown, Sheffan Chan, Michael L. Nelson, Johan Bollen\nSummary: We explore the availability and persistence of URLs cited in articles published in D-Lib Magazine. We extracted 4387 unique URLs referenced in 453 articles published from July 1995 to August 2004. The availability was checked three times a week for 25 weeks from September 2004 to February 2005. We found that approximately 28% of those URLs failed to resolve initially, and 30% failed to resolve at the last check. A majority of the unresolved URLs were due to 404 (page not found) and 500 (internal server error) errors. The content pointed to by the URLs was relatively stable; only 16% of the content registered more than a 1 KB change during the testing period. We explore possible factors which may cause a URL to fail by examining its age, path depth, top-level domain and file extension. Based on the data collected, we found the half-life of a URL referenced in a D-Lib Magazine article is approximately 10 years. We also found that URLs were more likely to be unavailable if they pointed to resources in the .net, .edu or country-specific top-level domain, used non-standard ports (i.e., not port 80), or pointed to resources with uncommon or deprecated extensions (e.g., .shtml, .ps, .txt).', name='academic_search', id='2dfa630a-a2c3-4e61-9954-646d7d05a22b', tool_call_id='call_5cc9773fe8fd43beaad4fe32'), AIMessage(content='', additional_kwargs={'refusal': None}, response_metadata={'token_usage': {'completion_tokens': 34, 'prompt_tokens': 20541, 'total_tokens': 20575, 'completion_tokens_details': {'accepted_prediction_tokens': None, 'audio_tokens': None, 'reasoning_tokens': 0, 'rejected_prediction_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 34}, 'prompt_tokens_details': {'audio_tokens': None, 'cached_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 20541}}, 'model_provider': 'openai', 'model_name': 'qwen3.5-plus', 'system_fingerprint': None, 'id': 'chatcmpl-abdbfc47-52a2-91a6-8930-bfd682ffc527', 'finish_reason': 'tool_calls', 'logprobs': None}, name='researcher', id='lc_run--019c9dd7-a49c-7683-af6f-c8cef2b3fc59-0', tool_calls=[{'name': 'wikipedia', 'args': {'__arg1': 'Peter A. Meyers'}, 'id': 'call_4b1a49eff09f48e2b68aa564', 'type': 'tool_call'}], invalid_tool_calls=[], usage_metadata={'input_tokens': 20541, 'output_tokens': 34, 'total_tokens': 20575, 'input_token_details': {}, 'output_token_details': {'reasoning': 0}}), ToolMessage(content='Error performing Wikipedia search: Expecting value: line 1 column 1 (char 0)', name='wikipedia', id='dae4bd5b-3b8e-4bca-b877-4d05f75b2e56', tool_call_id='call_4b1a49eff09f48e2b68aa564'), AIMessage(content='# Research Report: Identifying the Museum Founder\n\n## Problem Statement\n\nThe research task seeks to identify an individual with the following highly specific characteristics:\n- Founded a museum established between 1972 and 1975 (inclusive)\n- As of December 31, 2023, the museum is situated on the second floor of a building\n- The museum is located 24 to 25 miles (aerial distance) from a library that opened between 1992 and 1995 and is over 70,000 square feet\n- Was the editor and publisher of a magazine for over thirty years\n- Three marine species have been named in their honor\n- Had a parent with the first name Frank and a sibling with the first name Steve\n- Passed away on January 8 between 2021 and 2023 (inclusive) in a country different from their birthplace\n- Received an award in 2014 in recognition of their work\n\n## Research Findings\n\n### Death Date Investigation\n\nExtensive searches were conducted for notable individuals who died on January 8 between 2021 and 2023. The Wikipedia page for "Deaths in January 2022" was accessed and crawled, but the specific entry for January 8, 2022, did not yield a match that satisfied all the biographical criteria. The search for obituaries combining the death date with museum founder and magazine publisher status did not produce definitive results.\n\n### Marine Species Named After Individuals\n\nResearch into marine species etymology revealed several instances of organisms named after researchers and contributors:\n- Various marine species have been named after malacologists, underwater photographers, and marine researchers\n- Examples include species named after Dr. Otto Maas, Dr. Bernard John McAlice, Helmut Debelius, and Mike Severn\n- However, none of these individuals matched the complete profile including the specific death date, museum founding, and magazine publishing criteria\n\n### Museum and Magazine Publisher Connections\n\nSearches for museum founders who were also long-time magazine editors/publishers did not yield specific matches. The combination of:\n- Museum founded 1972-1975\n- Museum located on second floor of building\n- 30+ years as magazine editor/publisher\n- Award received in 2014\n\nCould not be linked to any specific individual through the available search results.\n\n### Family Name Information\n\nThe specific family details (parent named Frank, sibling named Steve) proved particularly difficult to verify through available search tools. This level of biographical detail typically requires access to comprehensive obituary databases or detailed biographical sources that were not accessible through the search tools used.\n\n### Geographic Constraints\n\nThe geographic requirements (museum 24-25 miles from a library opened 1992-1995, over 70,000 square feet; death in a country different from birthplace) could not be verified due to the inability to identify the specific individual and associated locations.\n\n### Information Gaps\n\nThe following critical information could not be confirmed:\n1. The specific name of the individual matching all criteria\n2. The name and location of the museum founded between 1972-1975\n3. The name of the magazine they edited/published for over 30 years\n4. The three specific marine species named in their honor\n5. Confirmation of parent named Frank and sibling named Steve\n6. The specific award received in 2014\n7. Birth and death countries\n8. The library located 24-25 miles from the museum\n\n## Conclusion\n\nBased on the comprehensive searches conducted using multiple tools (common_search, academic_search, wikipedia, and crawl_tool), I was unable to definitively identify the individual matching all the specified criteria. The combination of highly specific details suggests this is a real person with a documented biography, but the available search results did not contain sufficient interconnected information to make a positive identification.\n\nThe research was constrained by:\n- The maximum limit of 5 search tool calls\n- Search results that did not comprehensively link all the biographical criteria\n- Limited access to specialized obituary databases, marine species etymology databases, and museum founding records\n\nThe individual in question likely exists in historical records, but identifying them would require access to more specialized databases such as:\n- Comprehensive obituary archives with family details\n- Marine species etymology databases with honoree biographical information\n- Museum founding records with founder biographies\n- Magazine publisher historical registries\n- Award recipient databases from 2014\n\n## References\n\n- [Biographical Etymology of Marine Organism Names](https://www.bemon.loven.gu.se/petymol.m.html)\n\n- [Deaths in January 2022 - Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deaths_in_January_2022)\n\n- [List of species named after the COVID-19 pandemic - Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_species_named_after_the_COVID-19_pandemic)\n\n- [Five New Seahorse Species Discovered in Red Sea and Indonesian Waters](https://baijiahao.baidu.com/s?id=1826086105331525678)\n\n- [The Billionaires Who Died In 2022 - Forbes](https://www.forbes.com/sites/conormurray/2022/12/31/the-billionaires-who-died-in-2022/)\n\n- [2025 Annual Marine Photographer Competition Results](https://m.toutiao.com/a1850620858833992/)', additional_kwargs={}, response_metadata={}, name='researcher', id='d9e78ce9-6f9b-48b5-b7a3-7081f06a76e3', tool_calls=[], invalid_tool_calls=[]), HumanMessage(content='# Research Topic\n\nResearch Plan to Identify the Individual\n\n# Completed Research Steps\n\n## Completed Step 1: Search for Individual Matching Death Date and Biographical Details\n\n<finding>\n# Research Report: Identifying the Museum Founder\n\n## Problem Statement\n\nThe research task seeks to identify an individual with the following specific characteristics:\n- Founded a museum established between 1972 and 1975 (inclusive)\n- As of December 31, 2023, the museum is situated on the second floor of a building\n- The museum is located 24 to 25 miles (aerial distance) from a library that opened between 1992 and 1995 and is over 70,000 square feet\n- Was the editor and publisher of a magazine for over thirty years\n- Three marine species have been named in their honor\n- Had a parent with the first name Frank and a sibling with the first name Steve\n- Passed away on January 8 between 2021 and 2023 (inclusive) in a country different from their birthplace\n- Received an award in 2014 in recognition of their work\n\n## Research Findings\n\n### Search Strategy and Limitations\n\nMultiple search queries were executed using the available search tools (common_search and academic_search) to identify the individual matching these highly specific criteria. The searches focused on combinations of:\n- Death date (January 8, 2021-2023)\n- Museum founder status\n- Magazine publisher/editor role\n- Marine species named in honor\n- Family names (Frank as parent, Steve as sibling)\n\n### Key Search Results\n\n**Death Date Searches:**\nSearches for individuals who died on January 8 between 2021-2023 did not return specific matches that could be cross-referenced with the other criteria (museum founder, magazine publisher, marine species honors).\n\n**Marine Species Named After Individuals:**\nSome search results mentioned marine organisms named after various researchers and contributors, including:\n- Several species named after Dr. Otto Maas, Dr. Bernard John McAlice, and others\n- New seahorse species named after underwater photographers and divers (Helmut Debelius, Mike Severn)\n- However, none of these matched the complete profile of the individual in question\n\n**Museum and Magazine Publisher Connections:**\nSearches for museum founders who were also long-time magazine publishers did not yield specific matches with the death date and family name criteria.\n\n### Information Gaps\n\nThe following critical information could not be confirmed through the available searches:\n1. The specific name of the individual matching all criteria\n2. The name and location of the museum founded between 1972-1975\n3. The name of the magazine they edited/published for over 30 years\n4. The three specific marine species named in their honor\n5. Confirmation of parent named Frank and sibling named Steve\n6. The award received in 2014\n7. Birth and death countries to confirm they were different\n8. The library located 24-25 miles from the museum\n\n## Conclusion\n\nBased on the searches conducted, I was unable to definitively identify the individual matching all the specified criteria. The combination of highly specific details (exact death date of January 8, specific y